@Manasvibhatt297 please look closely at the instructions will gives when starting up - if you don't see them, you can see them in the screenshot from the [documentation](http://skoczen.github.io/will/#get-will-running-locally):

![uninitialized_env](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/200635/26677767/5a6d7c38-4721-11e7-9e65-74271c226b84.gif)

There's also explicit discussion of password and where to store credentials (environment variables - none of that stuff should live in `settings.py` in the docs as well: http://skoczen.github.io/will/config/

Exactly one of two things should happen when that code is executed:

1.) An exception is thrown to indicate out-of-bounds (probably std::out_of_range), as in:

std::vector<double> v(3);
v.at(6) = 9;

2.) Undefined behavior, similar to that of std::vector's square bracket operator, as in:

std::vector<double> v(3);
v[6] = 9;

I believe either of these is respectable behavior.  My personal preference (if you're asking it) would be for option 2, as C++ users should get used to having enough rope to hang themselves.  It comes with the territory and, while you have to be careful not to shoot yourself in the foot, the flip side is in performance and flexibility.

