Hi @crazyserb!

Try using either of these methods ([demo](http://jsfiddle.net/856bzzeL/592/)):

```js
$table
    .on('filterEnd', function () {
        console.log('filterEnd');
    })
    .on('search','.tablesorter-filter', function(e){
        console.log( e.type );
    });
```

\* Note the `search` method is binding to a [delegated event](http://api.jquery.com/on/#direct-and-delegated-events).

Hi @randdusing!

I think the easiest method would be to create a parser that replaces the "n/a" or "none" with an empty string ([demo](http://jsfiddle.net/abkNM/6160/))

```js
$.tablesorter.addParser({
    id: 'replace-na',
    is: function () {
        return false;
    },
    format: function (s) {
        return (s || '').replace('n/a', '');
    },
    type: 'text'
});
    
$(function () {
    $('table').tablesorter({
        theme: 'blue'
    });
});
```

I was going to suggest using the `data-text` attribute (data-attribute name set by the [`textAttribute` option](http://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#textattribute), but if you set it to an empty string, it will fallback to the text inside the cell. I'll fix it so you can set it to an empty string.

